'''Kasuga Shrine''' (かすがじんじゃ) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Mie Prefecture|ja|三重県|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Inabe City|ja|いなべ市|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its former shrine Rank is {{ill|Village Shrine|ja|村社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== 祭神 ==
{{ill|Sukunabikona no Mikoto|ja|少名彦命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ōyamatsumi no Kami|ja|大山祇神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kagatsurami no Kami|ja|火産霊神|1=Kagutsuchi|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yatsukuri-hiko no Kami|ja|八衢比古神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yatsukuri-hime no Kami|ja|八衢比売神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kunado no Kami|ja|岐の神|lt=Kunado no Kami|lt_ja=久那戸神（くなどのかみ）|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Iwanaga-hime no Mikoto|ja|磐長姫命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Take-mikazuchi no Kami|ja|武甕槌神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ame-no-Koyane no Mikoto|ja|天児屋根命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Futsunushi no Mikoto|ja|経津主命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Moshō no Megami|ja|罔象女神|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} are enshrined.

Among the enshrined deities, {{ill|Sukunabikona no Mikoto|ja|少名彦命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} is said to be “the deity whose spirit resides in stone”<ref>From the Mie Prefecture Shrine Record dated August 10, 12th year of Ōei, titled “The Stone Shrine Stone Festival and Stone-throwing Incident” (cited in 『三重県神社誌』).</ref>.

== 由緒 ==
The date and other details of {{ill|Enshrinement|ja|勧請|lt=Enshrinement|1=Kanjō|2=ja|3=分霊|4=es|5=Bunrei|6=id|7=Kanjō|8=zh|9=分靈|10=fr|11=Kanjō|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} are unknown. In ancient times, it was known as “Iharamiya”<ref>『角川日本地名大辞典』.</ref>. The Inabe District Local History Materials identifies this shrine as the “Stone Shrine” of the {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} “{{ill|Ise Province|ja|伊勢国|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}{{ill|Inabe District|ja|員弁郡|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} Stone Shrine,” enshrining {{ill|Sukunabikona no Mikoto|ja|少名彦命|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, and records that a sacred stone emitting light every night existed on the grounds. This stone was revered by {{ill|Harusumi Zennawa|ja|春澄善縄|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, who established the shrine and named it “Stone Shrine”<ref>Inabe District Office ed., 『員弁郡郷土資料』, Taishō 4 (1915).</ref>.

The 『伊勢輯雑記』 records that, as the principal shrine ({{ill|Main Shrine|ja|惣社|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) of the Shirose Seven Villages, it was once a grand shrine, while the Inabe Miscellany states that it is the tutelary deity ({{ill|Tutelary Deity|ja|産土神|1=Ubusunagami|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) of both Shimonojiri and Nishinojiri, remarking that “in ancient times, it was a magnificent shrine”<ref>『伊勢輯雑記』 by Matsumiya Yūsugu (from the people of Inabe District, born in Tenmei 7 (1787) – died in Kōka 2 (1845)). 『員弁雑誌』 was compiled by Okada Seidō in the early Meiji period as a corrected and supplemented section on Inabe District from 『伊勢輯雑記』.</ref>.

In the Village Detailed Account of the 7th year of {{ill|Bunsei period|ja|文政|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (1824), it is recorded as “Kasuga Daimyojin,” and in the Village Detailed Account of the 5th year of {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (1872) it is referred to as “Ishihara Shrine”<ref>Both of these Detailed Accounts are preserved in the {{ill|Tokugawa Hayashi Historical Institute|ja|徳川林政史研究所|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. The “Ishihara” seen in the Meiji account may be a misprint for “Ihara” (see 『三重県の地名』).</ref>. In Meiji 45, the small shrines dedicated to Hachitengū, Suijin, Yama-no-Kami, and the boundary deity were merged<ref>The Bunsei account lists “Atago, two Yama-no-Kami” as small village shrines, while the Meiji account lists “two Yama-no-Kami, Suijin, and Hashii no Kami.” Additionally, the Inabe Miscellany refers to Hachitengū as “Hachitengu-gu” and Atago as “without a shrine.”</ref>.

== 祭祀 ==
Prior to the Meiji period, the festival day was August 14 (as recorded in the Inabe Miscellany). According to the Inabe District Local History Materials, during the festival the parishioners ({{ill|Parishioner|ja|氏子|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) would offer white stones, after which a “stone-throwing ritual” was performed; however, during the {{ill|Ōei era|ja|応永|lt=Ōei era|lt_ja=応永年中|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (late 14th to early 15th century), this was supplanted by the {{ill|Stone Battle|ja|石合戦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and subsequently prohibited<ref>As noted in the previous reference on the “Stone Shrine Stone Festival and Stone-throwing Incident”: although offering stones before the shrine can be understood as relating to the deity whose spirit dwells in stone, there is no traditional basis for stone throwing, and due to its dangerous nature, it was prohibited except for shrine officials.</ref>.

=== 獅子舞 ===
The Lion Dance is performed on both October 9 and 10, and as of {{ill|Heisei period|ja|平成|lt=Heisei 22|lt_ja=22nd year|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (2010) it is said to have a history of over 300 years. The lion head currently in use is a valuable artifact created in the 2nd year of the {{ill|Kaei era|ja|嘉永|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (1849). The {{ill|Lion Dance|ja|獅子舞|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} is enacted with roles by the {{ill|Chinese Lion|ja|唐獅子|lt=Lion|lt_ja=獅子|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Tengu|ja|天狗|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}; the lion performs two dances—“Dance of the Frenzied Peony” and “Dance of the Chrysanthemum,” which represent spring and autumn—while the tengu accompanies the lion, guiding and assisting the performance. The lion dance, incorporating natural animal behaviors such as grooming ({{ill|Grooming|ja|グルーミング|lt=Fur Care|lt_ja=毛繕い|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) and sleeping while repelling calamities from all directions, is performed to pray for a bountiful harvest and the safety of the region. Additionally, festival music ({{ill|Hayashi|ja|囃子|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) is played, featuring children clad in kasuri-patterned kimonos with flower-crowned hats, who perform on instruments such as drums ({{ill|Taiko|ja|太鼓|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) and cymbals ({{ill|Bell|ja|鉦|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}) in time with an adult’s flute. The dance, known as the “Shimonojiri Kasuga Shrine Dedicated Lion Dance,” was designated as an {{ill|Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|無形民俗文化財|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} by Inabe City in May of {{ill|Shōwa period|ja|昭和|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} 58 (1983).

